'11:4': [
{sup:1, word:"lay", lines:["After all the enemies of Israel were subdued and David was exalted as the king of Israel, David committed a great sin while he was in a peaceful situation. This indicates that whenever we are at ease in a peaceful situation, it is easy for us to be seduced to indulge our flesh (cf. {1Pe4:1|1&nbsp;Pet. 4:1} and {1Pe4:1^4|note 4}). David&rsquo;s sin was the issue of his indulging of the lust of the eyes and the lust of the flesh (vv. {2Sa11:2|2b}-{2Sa11:3|3}). David, abusing the power of his kingship (vv. {2Sa11:4|4}-{2Sa11:5|5}), committed willful adultery by robbery. After committing such an act, David tried to cover his evil deed by means of a pretense (vv. {2Sa11:6|6}-{2Sa11:13|13}). Then he murdered Uriah, his faithful servant, by conspiring with Joab, so that he could take Uriah&rsquo;s wife (vv. {2Sa11:14|14}-{2Sa11:25|25}; {2Sa12:9|12:9}). David&rsquo;s behavior here was utterly different from that of Joseph, who ran and escaped from adultery ({Gen39:1|Gen. 39:1}-{Gen39:12|12}), and Boaz, who kept himself clean from the indulgence of the flesh of sin ({Rut3|Ruth 3}). By his one sin David broke the last five of the Ten Commandments ({Exo20:13|Exo. 20:13}-{Exo20:17|17}). David&rsquo;s sin was a great insult and offense to God, and it nearly annulled all his attainments from the past.","David, a man according to God&rsquo;s heart ({1Sa13:14|1&nbsp;Sam. 13:14}), was perfect in every way, but he failed in the matter of the indulgence of the lust of the flesh ({1Ki15:5|1&nbsp;Kings 15:5}). In this matter David was loose, and he sacrificed his high attainment in the pursuit of God. Even though he was a person of high attainment in his spiritual pursuit, he was still able to commit such a great sin. This should be a warning to all of us."]},
],
